    <activity>
  <title>Exploring Reciprocal Bearings</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this interactive activity, you will use the GeoGebra applet to explore the concept of bearings between two points. 
      As you move the points, observe how the bearings change and what relationship exists between the bearings of A from B and B from A.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <task>
    <ol>
      <li>Open the GeoGebra applet provided by your teacher or embedded on the page.</li>
      <li>Click and drag point <m>A</m> or point <m>B</m> to different positions on the coordinate plane.</li>
      <li>Observe how the <em>Bearing of B from A</em> and <em>Bearing of A from B</em> change dynamically.</li>
      <li>Record at least five different sets of bearings shown as you move the points.</li>
      <li>Try to determine a pattern or relationship between the two bearings.</li>
    </ol>
  </task>

  <discussion>
    <p>
      What did you notice about the two bearings? Share your observations with a classmate or in a small group.
    </p>
    <p>
      Try to answer the following:
    </p>
    <p>  
        <ul>
            <li>What is the sum of the two bearings in each case?</li>
            <li>How can you find the bearing of A from B if you know the bearing of B from A?</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
  </discussion>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      You should have discovered that the two bearings are <b>reciprocals</b>, meaning they differ by <m>180^\circ</m>.
      That is, if the bearing of B from A is <m>073^\circ</m>, then the bearing of A from B is <m>073^\circ + 180^\circ = 253^\circ</m>.
      If the sum is more than <m>360^\circ</m>, subtract <m>360^\circ</m> to stay within the standard bearing range.
    </p>
    <p>
      Understanding reciprocal bearings helps in navigation, map reading, and solving bearing problems in trigonometry.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</activity>

