    <note xml:id="note-remark">
        <title>Bearings</title>
        <p>
            Three figures are used to give the bearing.
        </p>
        <p>
            The angle is measured from the <em>north</em>.
        </p>
    </note>
    <p>
        For example, a bearing of <m>090°</m> indicates due <em>east</em>, <m>180°</m> 
        indicates due <em>south</em>, and <m>270°</m> indicates due <em>west</em>.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                 Kisumu and Nanyuki are situated in such a way that Nanyuki is on a bearing of 
                <m>075^\circ</m> from Nakuru and Kisumu on a bearing of <m>280^\circ</m> from Nakuru. 
                If Kisumu is <m>190</m> km and Nanyuki is <m>160</m> km from Nakuru, find the bearing of Kisumu from Nanyuki.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
              First, we draw a sketch showing the positions of Nakuru (N), Nanyuki (A), and Kisumu (B).
              The angle between the bearings from Nakuru to Nanyuki and Kisumu is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    \angle ANB = 280^\circ - 75^\circ = 205^\circ
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                 Since this angle is greater than 180°, we use the interior angle in triangle ANB:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                \angle ANB = 360^\circ - 205^\circ = 155^\circ
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
              Now, apply the cosine rule to find the distance <m>AB</m> (distance from Nanyuki to Kisumu):
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    AB^2 = AN^2 + NB^2 - 2 \cdot AN \cdot NB \cdot \cos(\angle ANB)
                </m>
            </p> 
            <p> 
                <m>
                    AB^2 = 160^2 + 190^2 - 2 \cdot 160 \cdot 190 \cdot \cos(155^\circ)
                </m>
            </p> 
            <p> 
                <m>
                    AB^2 = 25600 + 36100 - 2 \cdot 160 \cdot 190 \cdot \cos(155^\circ)
                </m>
            </p>
            <p> 
              <m>
                 AB^2 ≈ 25600 + 36100 - 60800 \cdot (-0.9063)
              </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                AB^2 ≈ 61700 + 55103.04 = 116803.04
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    AB ≈ \sqrt{116803.04} ≈ 341.8 \text{ km}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                 Now, use the sine rule to find the angle at Nanyuki (angle NAB):
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    \frac{\sin(\angle NAB)}{NB} = \frac{\sin(155^\circ)}{AB}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    \sin(\angle NAB) = \frac{190 \cdot \sin(155^\circ)}{341.8}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    \sin(\angle NAB) ≈ \frac{190 \cdot 0.4226}{341.8} ≈ 0.235
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    \angle NAB ≈ \sin^{-1}(0.235) ≈ 13.6^\circ
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
              Finally, the bearing of Kisumu from Nanyuki is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    075^\circ + 13.6^\circ = 088.6^\circ
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
              <em>Answers:</em>
            </p>
           <p>
            <ol>
                <li>The bearing of Kisumu from Nanyuki is approximately <m>089^\circ</m>.</li>
                <li>The distance from Nanyuki to Kisumu is approximately <m>342</m> km.</li>
              </ol>
           </p>
          </solution>
    </example>
